	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">qbradq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Say, that's a good idea <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /> Were you using a high pin-count MCU, shift registers or buffers?</div>
<br />I don't know that anyone has ever manufactured a CPU with enough IO, so I was using a PIC plus shift registers.  I didn't need 72 pins worth though, since the data and address lines for the CPU could be multiplexed with the PPU lines.  I figured I would never need to read from both CPU and PPU simultaneously.
<br />My goal was twofold:
<br />1. to dump carts
<br />2. to reprogram flash carts
<br />
<br />The schematics are pretty simple, though I would probably use Arduino if doing it over again today.  I would pick up and finish the project in a heartbeat if the mechanical side (specifically the 72 pin connector) weren't such a problem.  I've often wondered if it would be cost effective to spend a couple of thousand dollars to have a run of the connectors made.  I doubt there's much of a market for them, but over many years you might be able to sell all of them.  Maybe Kevin would buy a bunch for when he manufactures his KevTendo <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />
<br />
<br />Edit: found my old schematic laying around.  I can take a photo of the pcb's too if anyone cares, they're sitting in a drawer somewhere.
<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://dl.dropbox.com/u/477050/copycart_schematic.pdf">http://dl.dropbox.com/u/477050/copycart_schematic.pdf</a><!-- m -->

		

		</td>
