	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I understand exactly what you're saying.
<br />
<br />The thing that really made these connectors work was the fact there was only .019" of free play.  So you're unable to slid the cart fully to the left and create the scenario seen in the picture you show.
<br />
<br />To prove it to myself I place a board with all 72 contacts removed from the case in my connector.  Then I tested for continuity and shorting between pins on both sides and the center while the board was slid from side to side.  By testing in this manner I can rule out the argument that my cart isn't using all the pins.  Now I didn't test every single pin in every single position because that I'd still be testing.  But I did test the extremes that have the best chance of causing issues.  If I didn't already have everything assembled I would be willing to do more tests to further prove things if someone desired.  If I buy more connectors in the future I will most likely do such just to prove even more so for myself.
<br />
<br />The only real way I see problems arising is if certain carts have different lengths of the board edge.  If the board was small enough you may be able short pins together or lose contact.  One could go through and measure various carts with a caliper if they were that concerned.
<br />
<br />As an aside I'm not necessarily trying to prove you "wrong" I agree there is potential for issues with these connectors.  And if you don't want to use them I'm not going to lose any sleep.  It's not like I'm trying to sell them to anyone.  After buying them I everyone informed me they wouldn't work and gave evidence on paper that they wouldn't.  At the time I regretted buying them and expected to return them.   But with some simple testing with the actual hardware I couldn't find any actual problems.  Personally I'm thrilled with them and very thankful that I actually tested things out and found a solution for at least myself, if no one wants to agree with my results that's fine.  They can continue to search for a solution.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
